 Nabokov's passionate interest in the mystery of time, which influenced many of his novels, including the late masterpiece Ada.Insomniac Dreams, edited by leading Nabokov authority Gennady Barabtarlo, presents the text of Nabokov's dream experiment, illustrated with a selection of his original index cards, and provides rich annotations and analysis that put them in the context of his life and writings. The book also includes previously unpublished records of Nabokov's dreams from his letters and notebooks and shows important connections between his fiction and private writings on dreams and time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aDreams. 0aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union. 0aTime. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh1 aBarabtarlo, Gennady, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarabtarlo, Gennady.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060659140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400888962zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400888962423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781400888962/original  a978-3-11-060659-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK